<item>
            <title>[SPARK-48019] ColumnVectors with dictionaries and nulls are not read/copied correctly</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SPARK-48019</link>
                <project id="12315420" key="SPARK">Spark</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;ColumnVectors&lt;/tt&gt; have APIs like &lt;tt&gt;getInts&lt;/tt&gt;, &lt;tt&gt;getFloats&lt;/tt&gt; and so on. Those return a primitive array with the contents of the vector. When the ColumnVector has a dictionary, the values are decoded with the dictionary before filling in the primitive array.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, &lt;tt&gt;ColumnVectors&lt;/tt&gt; can have nulls, and for those &lt;tt&gt;null&lt;/tt&gt; entries, the dictionary id is irrelevant, and can also be invalid. The dictionary should not be used for the &lt;tt&gt;null&lt;/tt&gt; entries of the vector. Sometimes, this can cause an &lt;tt&gt;ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException&lt;/tt&gt; .&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In addition to the possible Exception, copying a &lt;tt&gt;ColumnarArray&lt;/tt&gt; is not correct. A &lt;tt&gt;ColumnarArray&lt;/tt&gt; contains a &lt;tt&gt;ColumnVector&lt;/tt&gt; so it can contain &lt;tt&gt;null&lt;/tt&gt; values. However, the &lt;tt&gt;copy()&lt;/tt&gt; for primitive types does not take into account the null-ness of the entries, and blindly copies all the primitive values. That means the null entries get lost.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
